CAN,G7EXnvfqqsM,UgyzCS_N5XdcjP3WHGZ4AaABAg,,@Gurskikh11,"========-------------- Trump in China: What Traps Should the U.S. and China Avoid? — FTFY
As the leaders of the United States and China met in Beijing on May 14, Xi Jinping asked Trump: Can China and the United States overcome the so-called Thucydides trap? Google ""5 Traps for Trump and Xi""...
Here are five traps that will shape the next phase of U.S.-China relations—traps that both countries must avoid:
1. The Thucydides Trap: It describes a tendency toward war when a rising power threatens to displace an existing power as the regional or international hegemon.
2. The Hobbesian Trap: It explains why preemptive strikes occur between two groups due to mutual fear of an imminent attack, leading to a cycle of mistrust and conflict escalation, casein point ""Taiwan""..
3. The Jevons Trap: It is, in a geopolitical context, a trap in which increased efficiency, security, or defensive barriers within a system—such as the implementation of strict cyber defenses and trade barriers—actually accelerate the aggressive pursuit of the very resource being guarded.
4. The Tacitus Trap: It describes a situation in which, when a government or leader becomes deeply unpopular or generates significant mistrust, any action they take—whether good or bad—will be viewed with intense hostility and suspicion by their counterpart...
5. The Kindleberger Trap: It describes the risks associated with the failure of a leading power to provide global public goods—such as economic stability and security—during periods of transition in global leadership.
China does not view the Thucydides Trap as a predictive model, but rather as a threat that can and must be avoided. 
If China and the U.S. fail, the danger will likely manifest first through decline before spiraling into disaster; The reason why the Kindleberger Trap should concern Washington more than the ancient Greek trap.

